        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer28681407" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3045441427408479944">Okay, I like this book but I have some problems with it. I was really hoping for a feel good story and it was kind of disappointing. I liked the idea of the Wednesday letters. It is sweet to think that a husband would do this. I like the idea of redemption that is discussed in the story but it really bothers me when LDS authors don&apos;t just make their characters LDS! I mean what is the big deal? It wouldn&apos;t be like they would have to explain everything about our faith but if you&apos;re going to have c</span>
  <span id="freeText3045441427408479944" style="display:none">Okay, I like this book but I have some problems with it. I was really hoping for a feel good story and it was kind of disappointing. I liked the idea of the Wednesday letters. It is sweet to think that a husband would do this. I like the idea of redemption that is discussed in the story but it really bothers me when LDS authors don't just make their characters LDS! I mean what is the big deal? It wouldn't be like they would have to explain everything about our faith but if you're going to have characters who have a journey of faith why do they have to be non-denominational Christians?<br />Richard Paul Evans does similar things and it makes me wonder!<br />I guess they are worried that other people don't understand our culture but so many books detail the Catholics and Jews and their religions and traditions. So maybe it is just that they can't sell but wouldn't it be cool to have a main stream Mormon character that was just a normal person. That struggles and overcomes? </span>
  <a data-text-id="3045441427408479944" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
